{
  "id": "exhaust-arbitrage",
  "name": "Exhaust Arbitrage",
  "desc": "User prompts, feedback, usage patterns, and reasoning traces are valuable byproducts that the processor captures internally because no mature market prices them. The clause not in the contract becomes the economic centre of the deal — arbitrage on unpriced exhaust.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Frontier",
      "memo": "Exhaust arbitrage occurs at frontier capability where interaction data from powerful models generates the most valuable unclaimed byproduct.",
      "detail": "Frontier capability generates the richest exhaust because sophisticated model interactions produce chain-of-thought traces, preference signals, and usage patterns of highest value. The frontier position means the exhaust has no established market price because the capability creating it is novel. Frontier models generate exhaust that is qualitatively different from narrow model outputs. The capability level determines the quality and strategic value of the unclaimed byproduct."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "General",
      "memo": "General domain breadth maximizes exhaust value because interaction data spans every topic and use case the model encounters across all domains.",
      "detail": "General domain means the model produces exhaust across every subject area, creating a comprehensive dataset of human-AI interaction patterns. This breadth makes the exhaust more valuable than single-domain interaction data because it captures cross-domain intelligence. General breadth means the exhaust market is potentially larger than any single application domain. The domain breadth determines the scope and versatility of the arbitrage opportunity."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Rapid",
      "memo": "Rapid capability trajectory increases exhaust value because each model improvement generates new interaction data that captures evolving usage patterns.",
      "detail": "Rapid trajectory means new model versions create fresh exhaust streams as users explore improved capabilities and reveal new interaction patterns. The pace of improvement ensures that exhaust remains a continuously generating resource rather than a static dataset. Each capability improvement creates a new vintage of interaction data with distinct properties and value. Rapid trajectory drives the urgency of exhaust capture because the window for each data vintage is temporary."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "AI-assisted",
      "memo": "AI-assisted research generates high-value exhaust because model-researcher interactions produce reasoning traces and experimental feedback of exceptional quality.",
      "detail": "AI-assisted research means human researchers using AI tools generate exhaust that captures expert reasoning, experimental design, and problem-solving approaches. This exhaust is more valuable than casual user interactions because it captures high-skill cognitive processes. The AI-assisted research context produces exhaust that directly improves subsequent model capability. Research interaction exhaust is the arbitrage opportunity with the highest per-interaction value."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Tool-using",
      "memo": "Tool-using unhobbling generates exhaust from tool interactions, API calls, and workflow patterns that reveal how humans integrate AI into practical work.",
      "detail": "Tool-using unhobbling means the model generates exhaust from real operational tool use, not just conversational interaction. Tool-use exhaust includes API call patterns, error handling approaches, and workflow integration data. This operational exhaust is more commercially valuable than conversational exhaust because it captures real work patterns. Tool-using exhaust reveals how organizations actually deploy AI capability in production environments."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Population-scale",
      "memo": "Population-scale replication generates massive exhaust volumes because millions of concurrent interactions produce an enormous continuous stream of interaction data.",
      "detail": "Population-scale means millions of users generate exhaust simultaneously, creating a dataset that no single organization could commission or purchase. The scale is what makes exhaust arbitrage economically significant rather than merely interesting. Volume enables statistical analysis, pattern detection, and preference learning that small datasets cannot support. Population-scale exhaust is the raw material from which arbitrage extracts competitive advantage."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Faster-than-human",
      "memo": "Faster-than-human operating speed means exhaust accumulates at machine rate, generating datasets far faster than any deliberate data collection programme.",
      "detail": "Faster-than-human speed means exhaust generation outpaces any traditional data collection or curation process. The model processes interactions and generates byproduct data continuously at rates that make manual data gathering obsolete. Speed of accumulation is a competitive advantage because early exhaust capture creates compounding data advantages. The operating speed determines how quickly the arbitrage position builds and how fast the uncaptured value accumulates."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
      "memo": "Exhaust arbitrage operates in the cognitive domain where interaction data, preference signals, and reasoning traces are all information-layer byproducts.",
      "detail": "Cognitive-only extension means the exhaust is purely informational, consisting of interaction patterns, preferences, and reasoning traces. There is no physical-world exhaust generation in this stance. The cognitive domain is where the most valuable AI exhaust is generated because it captures thinking patterns and decision processes. Cognitive-only focus keeps the stance cleanly about information economics rather than physical-world data collection."
    },
    "Role": {
      "value": "Assistant",
      "memo": "The assistant role generates the richest exhaust because users reveal thinking patterns, preferences, and decision processes through natural interaction with helpful AI.",
      "detail": "Assistant role means users interact freely and reveal cognitive processes they would not expose through formal tool use or surveys. The helpful interaction context makes users comfortable sharing detailed reasoning, preferences, and decision-making approaches. Assistant interactions generate exhaust that is more authentic and valuable than data from structured collection instruments. The assistant role is the natural setting where unclaimed byproduct generation is most prolific and commercially valuable."
    },
    "Actuation": {
      "value": "Informational",
      "memo": "Exhaust arbitrage operates through informational channels where the byproduct value lies in captured knowledge, preferences, and behavioral patterns.",
      "detail": "Informational actuation means the exhaust consists of information artifacts rather than physical or financial actions. The value lies in what the interaction data reveals about user behavior, preferences, and reasoning processes. Informational exhaust is the most versatile byproduct because it can be applied to model improvement, product development, and market intelligence. The informational channel is where unclaimed data value accumulates most rapidly and with least visibility."
    },
    "Autonomy": {
      "value": "Stateless task",
      "memo": "Each stateless interaction generates independent exhaust, creating a continuously accumulating byproduct stream without requiring persistent autonomous system operation.",
      "detail": "Stateless task means each user interaction independently generates exhaust without requiring the system to maintain long-term autonomous objectives. The exhaust accumulates through volume of independent interactions rather than through persistent system behavior. Stateless exhaust generation is particularly valuable because each interaction captures a complete cognitive snapshot. The stateless character means exhaust value compounds through aggregation rather than through persistent system action."
    },
    "Delegated Authority": {
      "value": "None",
      "memo": "No delegated authority is needed for exhaust capture because the byproduct is generated automatically as a side effect of normal system operation.",
      "detail": "No delegated authority means exhaust capture occurs without any explicit delegation or authorization from the user. The user delegates nothing; the exhaust is simply generated as a technical byproduct of the interaction they initiated. This absence of explicit authority delegation is precisely what makes the exhaust unclaimed and available for arbitrage. No delegated authority is the defining characteristic that makes exhaust economically distinct from commissioned data."
    },
    "Tool Access": {
      "value": "Gated tools",
      "memo": "Gated tool access generates exhaust from each tool interaction, with API calls and tool use patterns creating valuable byproduct data about operational workflows.",
      "detail": "Gated tools means each tool interaction passes through interfaces that can capture usage patterns, error rates, and workflow sequences. The tool gates serve double duty as both access control and exhaust collection points. Tool-use exhaust is commercially valuable because it reveals how organizations integrate AI into production workflows. Gated tool access demonstrates that infrastructure design determines both functionality and exhaust capture capability."
    },
    "Response / Intervention Capability": {
      "value": "Manual stop",
      "memo": "Manual stop capability means users can terminate interactions but cannot retroactively prevent exhaust capture from interactions already completed.",
      "detail": "Manual stop means the user can end their session but the exhaust from completed interactions has already been captured by the processor. This asymmetry between user control over interaction and lack of control over exhaust is fundamental to the arbitrage pattern. The user's stop capability does not extend to the byproduct their interaction generated. Manual stop demonstrates that interaction control is not the same as exhaust control."
    },
    "Command Actor": {
      "value": "Enterprise",
      "memo": "Enterprise command means the AI provider's corporate leadership decides how to exploit exhaust, with users having no command authority over byproduct disposition.",
      "detail": "Enterprise command means corporate governance of the AI provider controls exhaust strategy, not individual users or external parties. Users generate the exhaust but the provider's enterprise leadership decides whether to prop-trade, sell, or discard it. This command asymmetry is the governance expression of the exhaust arbitrage pattern. Enterprise command over user-generated byproduct is the structural dynamic that makes exhaust capture economically valuable."
    },
    "Decision Tempo": {
      "value": "Product cycle",
      "memo": "Exhaust arbitrage decisions follow product-cycle tempo as corporate strategy evolves from internal model improvement to potential external commercialization.",
      "detail": "Product cycle tempo means exhaust exploitation strategy evolves through normal corporate planning and product development cycles. The decision to transition from internal arbitrage to external exhaust sales typically follows established product development timelines. Product-cycle governance enables deliberate strategy development without the urgency that race dynamics create. The tempo reflects that exhaust commercialization is a strategic business decision, not an emergency response."
    },
    "Tradeoff Authority": {
      "value": "Product team",
      "memo": "Product team authority makes the tradeoffs between exhaust capture, user privacy, and model improvement that determine the arbitrage strategy.",
      "detail": "Product team authority means the engineers and product managers who build the AI system decide what exhaust to capture and how to use it. These tradeoffs between data capture scope, privacy impact, and improvement value are made within normal product development processes. The product team's decisions determine whether exhaust is used for internal model improvement, external data products, or discarded. Product team authority over exhaust strategy is appropriate at the arbitrage stage before markets or regulation develop."
    },
    "Permission": {
      "value": "Silent",
      "memo": "Exhaust capture operates under silent permission where users agree to broad terms of service without understanding that interaction data becomes a valuable byproduct.",
      "detail": "Silent permission means the user technically consented through terms of service but has no practical understanding of exhaust capture. The permission is legally present but informationally empty, with terms of service too broad for meaningful informed consent. Silent permission is the defining rights characteristic of the arbitrage stage before transparency or regulation emerges. The silence is what enables unclaimed byproduct capture without explicit negotiation or value sharing."
    },
    "Regulatory Posture": {
      "value": "Permissive",
      "memo": "Exhaust arbitrage operates under permissive regulatory posture in the early market stage before regulation specifically addresses AI interaction data as a distinct category.",
      "detail": "Permissive regulation reflects the early-stage reality where AI interaction data falls into regulatory gaps between existing frameworks. Data protection law may apply to personal data within exhaust but does not specifically address aggregate behavioral patterns. The permissive posture enables arbitrage without explicit regulatory authorization or prohibition. Permissive regulation is the market-formation stage where exhaust exploitation precedes specific regulatory attention."
    },
    "Data Availability": {
      "value": "Proprietary owned",
      "memo": "Exhaust is treated as proprietary data owned by the processor under terms of service, making it available only to the capturing entity for internal use.",
      "detail": "Proprietary owned availability means the exhaust exists only within the processor's systems with no external access or market availability. The processor treats interaction data as its own proprietary asset under broad terms-of-service language. This proprietary treatment is what enables arbitrage, as no external market or licensing framework exists yet. Proprietary ownership of exhaust is the default that persists until data producers assert competing claims."
    },
    "Provenance": {
      "value": "Mixed/declared",
      "memo": "Exhaust provenance is mixed because it combines user inputs, model outputs, system metadata, and interaction patterns from diverse, poorly documented sources.",
      "detail": "Mixed/declared provenance means the exhaust contains data from many users, interaction types, and temporal contexts without systematic attribution. The provenance is declared in aggregate terms but individual data items lack clean origin documentation. Mixed provenance complicates future claims because it is unclear which user interactions generated which valuable patterns. The mixed character is a feature of the arbitrage stage before systematic provenance tracking is commercially required."
    },
    "Model-Weight Rights": {
      "value": "Hosted only",
      "memo": "Hosted-only model access means users interact through the provider's platform, ensuring all exhaust is captured within the provider's infrastructure boundary.",
      "detail": "Hosted-only access means the provider controls the interaction boundary and all exhaust generation occurs within their infrastructure. Users cannot self-host, cannot inspect what exhaust is captured, and cannot prevent collection. Hosted-only is the model-weight arrangement that maximizes exhaust capture opportunity. The hosting arrangement is architecturally designed to ensure complete exhaust capture, even if that was not the stated design purpose."
    },
    "Territory": {
      "value": "Cross-border",
      "memo": "Exhaust arbitrage operates cross-border because users interact from multiple jurisdictions, creating exhaust subject to diverse and potentially conflicting data regimes.",
      "detail": "Cross-border territory means exhaust contains interaction data from users across many jurisdictions with different data protection rules. The cross-border character creates regulatory complexity because different jurisdictions may claim authority over exhaust from their residents. Prop-trading is simpler than external sales because internal use faces less jurisdictional scrutiny than commercial data distribution. Cross-border exhaust generates the diversity that makes the dataset valuable but also the regulatory complexity that future monetization must navigate."
    },
    "Data Subject Exposure": {
      "value": "Ordinary personal data",
      "memo": "Exhaust contains ordinary personal data embedded in interaction patterns, preferences, and behavioral signals that are personally identifiable in aggregate.",
      "detail": "Ordinary personal data exposure means exhaust contains interaction patterns and preferences that can identify individual users or reveal personal characteristics. Aggregate behavioral data can be re-identified even when individual messages appear anonymous. The personal data character creates data protection obligations that arbitrage may not adequately address. Ordinary personal data in exhaust is the trigger that eventually activates regulatory attention and user rights claims."
    },
